# Network Health Manager — Server Setup Documentation

## Overview

The Network Health Manager (NHM) is a FastAPI/Uvicorn backend paired with a React + Vite frontend. It provides ping, port scanning, DNS lookup, and AI-powered analysis via Ollama. This document covers the full server-side setup required to expose the app from a homelab Ubuntu Server VM to the internet securely.

## Infrastructure Constraints

- **ISP:** A CGNAT provider — no public IP, no inbound port forwarding possible
- **Hypervisor:** Proxmox with GPU passthrough (GTX 1650)
- **Solution:** Cloudflare Tunnel bypasses CGNAT entirely — no open inbound ports required

## Architecture

```
Browser → Cloudflare Edge (Hong Kong) → cloudflared tunnel → Nginx :80/:443
                                                                  ├── location /        → /var/www/nethealth.example.com/ (React static files)
                                                                  └── location /api/    → Uvicorn :8000 (FastAPI)
                                                                                              └── Ollama :11434 (locked to 127.0.0.1)
```

## Stack

| Component | Role |
|---|---|
| Ubuntu Server 24.04 | Host OS on Proxmox VM |
| Nginx | Reverse proxy + static file server |
| cloudflared | Outbound tunnel to Cloudflare |
| Certbot (snap) | SSL certificate management via DNS challenge |
| Fail2ban | Brute force and abuse protection |
| UFW | Host firewall |
| FastAPI / Uvicorn | Python API backend, port 8000 |
| Ollama | Local LLM inference, locked to 127.0.0.1:11434 |
| React + Vite | Frontend, built to `/var/www/nethealth.example.com/` |

