## Phase 1 — Nginx Installation and Configuration

Install Nginx on the Ubuntu VM and configure it as a reverse proxy that forwards API traffic to Uvicorn and serves the React frontend directly as static files.

### Step 1.1 — Update the system

```bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
```

### Step 1.2 — Install Nginx

```bash
sudo apt install nginx -y
```

### Step 1.3 — Enable and verify Nginx

```bash
sudo systemctl enable nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

Expected: `active (running)`

### Step 1.4 — Fix server_tokens in nginx.conf

Ubuntu's default `nginx.conf` ships with `server_tokens build` in the http block — this exposes the version number plus build details. Set it globally to off before creating any site config.

```bash
sudo nano /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
```

Change `server_tokens build` to `server_tokens off` in the http block.

### Step 1.5 — Create the web root directory

Nginx serves the built React frontend from `/var/www/nethealth.example.com/`. This directory must be owned by `www-data` so Nginx can read it and the deploy script can write to it.

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/nethealth.example.com
sudo chown www-data:www-data /var/www/nethealth.example.com
sudo chmod 755 /var/www/nethealth.example.com
```

### Step 1.6 — Create the site configuration

```bash
sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/nethealth.example.com
```

Initial config (pre-SSL, pre-hardening):

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name nethealth.example.com;

    root /var/www/nethealth.example.com;
    index index.html;

    # Serve React frontend — fallback to index.html for client-side routing
    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }

    # Proxy API requests to Uvicorn
    location /api/ {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
```

**Config notes:**

- `root /var/www/nethealth.example.com` — where the built React app lives after `deploy.sh` runs
- `try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html` — required for React Router; falls back to `index.html` so client-side routes work on refresh
- `location /api/` — all FastAPI routes are prefixed with `/api/` via `APIRouter(prefix="/api")` in `main.py`
- `server_name nethealth.example.com` only — do not add `www.nethealth.example.com` unless a cert is obtained for it

### Step 1.7 — Disable the default Nginx site

The default site (`/etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default`) catches all requests that don't match a server_name. Remove it to prevent unintended public exposure.

```bash
sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
```

### Step 1.8 — Enable the site

```bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/nethealth.example.com /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
```

### Step 1.9 — Test and reload

```bash
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

