## Phase 4 — Server Hardening

### Step 4.1 — UFW firewall

```bash
sudo ufw allow 22/tcp
sudo ufw allow 80/tcp
sudo ufw allow 443/tcp
sudo ufw allow out 7844/tcp
sudo ufw enable
```

Port 7844 outbound is required for `cloudflared`. All other inbound ports are denied by default.

Verify:

```bash
sudo ufw status verbose
```

Expected output:

```
Status: active
Default: deny (incoming), allow (outgoing)

To                   Action    From
--                   ------    ----
22                   ALLOW IN  Anywhere
80/tcp               ALLOW IN  Anywhere
443/tcp              ALLOW IN  Anywhere
7844/tcp             ALLOW OUT Anywhere
```

### Step 4.2 — Hardened Nginx configuration

Replace the initial site config with the full hardened version at `/etc/nginx/sites-available/nethealth.example.com`.

This config adds: rate limiting zones, direct IP access blocking, real IP resolution from the Cloudflare tunnel, security headers, the Cloudflare IP whitelist on port 443, and the SSL certificate block.

```nginx
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=general:10m rate=30r/m;
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=expensive:10m rate=10r/m;

# Block direct IP access — drops connection with no response
server {
    listen 80 default_server;
    server_name _;
    return 444;
}

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name nethealth.example.com;

    # Resolve real client IP from Cloudflare tunnel.
    # The tunnel forwards requests from 127.0.0.1 — without this, all clients
    # appear as 127.0.0.1, breaking rate limiting and fail2ban.
    set_real_ip_from 127.0.0.1;
    real_ip_header X-Forwarded-For;

    # Security headers
    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000" always;
    add_header X-Frame-Options "SAMEORIGIN" always;
    add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;

    # Serve React frontend
    root /var/www/nethealth.example.com;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        limit_req zone=general burst=10 nodelay;
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }

    # Expensive API routes — tighter rate limit
    location ~ ^/api/(hosts/[^/]+/(scan|ping|analyze)|dns/(lookup|analyze))$ {
        limit_req zone=expensive burst=5 nodelay;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }

    # All other API routes
    location /api/ {
        limit_req zone=general burst=10 nodelay;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name nethealth.example.com;
    server_tokens off;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/nethealth.example.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/nethealth.example.com/privkey.pem;

    # Allow tunnel
    allow 127.0.0.1;

    # Cloudflare IP whitelist — blocks non-Cloudflare traffic on port 443
    allow 173.245.48.0/20;
    allow 103.21.244.0/22;
    allow 103.22.200.0/22;
    allow 103.31.4.0/22;
    allow 141.101.64.0/18;
    allow 108.162.192.0/18;
    allow 190.93.240.0/20;
    allow 188.114.96.0/20;
    allow 197.234.240.0/22;
    allow 198.41.128.0/17;
    allow 162.158.0.0/15;
    allow 104.16.0.0/13;
    allow 104.24.0.0/14;
    allow 172.64.0.0/13;
    allow 131.0.72.0/22;
    deny all;

    # Security headers
    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000" always;
    add_header X-Frame-Options "SAMEORIGIN" always;
    add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;

    set_real_ip_from 127.0.0.1;
    real_ip_header X-Forwarded-For;

    # Serve React frontend
    root /var/www/nethealth.example.com;
    index index.html;

    location / {
        limit_req zone=general burst=10 nodelay;
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
    }

    # Expensive API routes — tighter rate limit
    location ~ ^/api/(hosts/[^/]+/(scan|ping|analyze)|dns/(lookup|analyze))$ {
        limit_req zone=expensive burst=5 nodelay;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }

    # All other API routes
    location /api/ {
        limit_req zone=general burst=10 nodelay;
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
```

**Rate limiting zones:**

- `general` — 30 requests/minute, burst 10: applied to all routes
- `expensive` — 10 requests/minute, burst 5: applied to scan, ping, analyze, and DNS routes

**Why two port blocks (80 and 443):** The tunnel routes to port 80. Port 443 exists for direct HTTPS connections and carries the Cloudflare IP whitelist. Both blocks are needed. On CGNAT, no external traffic can reach port 443 directly anyway — the whitelist is defense in depth.

Test and reload after saving:

```bash
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

### Step 4.3 — Fail2ban Nginx jails

Add to `/etc/fail2ban/jail.local` below the existing `[sshd]` block:

```ini
[nginx-http-auth]
enabled = true
port = http,https
logpath = /var/log/nginx/error.log
maxretry = 5
bantime = 24h
findtime = 600

[nginx-limit-req]
enabled = true
port = http,https
logpath = /var/log/nginx/error.log
maxretry = 10
bantime = 24h
findtime = 600
```

Restart fail2ban and confirm all three jails are active:

```bash
sudo systemctl restart fail2ban
sudo fail2ban-client status
```

Expected: `Jail list: nginx-http-auth, nginx-limit-req, sshd`

### Step 4.4 — Verify security headers are active

With the app running, confirm headers are being sent:

```bash
curl -I -H "Host: nethealth.example.com" http://127.0.0.1
```

Expected in response:

```
strict-transport-security: max-age=31536000
x-frame-options: SAMEORIGIN
x-content-type-options: nosniff
```

