## Phase 5 — App Migration

Deploy the FastAPI backend and React frontend to the Ubuntu VM. By the end of this phase, the full application stack is running and publicly accessible at `https://nethealth.example.com`.

### Step 5.1 — Install Node.js v22

Node.js is required to build the React frontend. Install via the NodeSource repository to get a current version — Ubuntu's default apt package is outdated.

```bash
curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_22.x | sudo -E bash -
sudo apt install nodejs -y
node --version   # should return v22.x.x
```

### Step 5.2 — Install Ollama

Ollama runs the local LLM used for AI analysis. Install using the official installer:

```bash
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
```

The installer registers Ollama as a systemd service. Confirm it started:

```bash
sudo systemctl status ollama
```

### Step 5.3 — Lock Ollama to localhost

By default, Ollama may bind to `0.0.0.0`, exposing the API on all interfaces. Lock it to `127.0.0.1` so it is only accessible from the local machine.

```bash
sudo systemctl edit ollama
```

Add under `[Service]`:

```ini
[Service]
Environment="OLLAMA_HOST=127.0.0.1"
```

Apply and verify:

```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart ollama
ss -tlnp | grep 11434
```

Expected: `127.0.0.1:11434` — not `0.0.0.0:11434`.

### Step 5.4 — Pull the Ollama model

```bash
ollama pull llama3.2
ollama list
```

Expected: `llama3.2:latest` listed with size ~2.0 GB.

### Step 5.5 — Clone the repository

```bash
cd ~
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/network-health-manager.git
cd network-health-manager
```

### Step 5.6 — Create the Python virtual environment

```bash
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Verify Uvicorn is available:

```bash
which uvicorn
# Expected: /home/youruser/network-health-manager/venv/bin/uvicorn
```

### Step 5.7 — Configure the environment file

```bash
cp .env.example .env
nano .env
```

Set all required values. At minimum:

```ini
OLLAMA_MODEL=llama3.2
```

Lock down permissions — the `.env` file contains secrets and must not be world-readable:

```bash
chmod 600 .env
```

### Step 5.8 — Create the systemd service

Create a systemd service so Uvicorn starts automatically on boot and restarts on failure.

```bash
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/nhm.service
```

Contents:

```ini
[Unit]
Description=Network Health Manager
After=network.target ollama.service
Wants=ollama.service

[Service]
User=youruser
WorkingDirectory=/home/youruser/network-health-manager
ExecStart=/home/youruser/network-health-manager/venv/bin/uvicorn api.main:app --host 127.0.0.1 --port 8000
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=5
EnvironmentFile=/home/youruser/network-health-manager/.env

# Hardening
NoNewPrivileges=true
PrivateTmp=true
ProtectSystem=strict
ProtectHome=read-only
ReadWritePaths=/home/youruser/network-health-manager/logs

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

**Service notes:**

- `After=ollama.service` and `Wants=ollama.service` — ensures Ollama is up before the app starts, since the analyze endpoints depend on it
- `EnvironmentFile` — loads `.env` into the service environment so FastAPI picks up config values
- `ProtectSystem=strict` and `ProtectHome=read-only` — systemd hardening; prevents the process from writing anywhere except the explicitly allowed `logs/` directory
- `--host 127.0.0.1` — Uvicorn only listens on localhost; Nginx is the only entry point

Enable and start:

```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable nhm
sudo systemctl start nhm
sudo systemctl status nhm
```

Expected: `active (running)`

### Step 5.9 — Build and deploy the frontend

The `deploy.sh` script at the repo root handles the full frontend deployment: builds the React app, copies the output to the Nginx web root, and restarts the NHM service.

```bash
cat deploy.sh
```

Make it executable and symlink it for convenience:

```bash
chmod +x deploy.sh
sudo ln -s /home/youruser/network-health-manager/deploy.sh /usr/local/bin/deploy-nhm
```

Run the first deployment:

```bash
deploy-nhm
```

This builds `client/dist/` and copies it to `/var/www/nethealth.example.com/`. After this completes, visiting `https://nethealth.example.com` should serve the React app.

> **Note:** Run `deploy-nhm` after every pull that includes frontend changes. Backend-only changes only require `sudo systemctl restart nhm`.

### Step 5.10 — Verify the full stack

```bash
# 1. Uvicorn is running on the correct address
ss -tlnp | grep 8000
# Expected: 127.0.0.1:8000

# 2. Ollama is running and locked to localhost
ss -tlnp | grep 11434
# Expected: 127.0.0.1:11434

# 3. NHM service is active
sudo systemctl status nhm --no-pager

# 4. API is responding
curl http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/hosts
# Expected: JSON response (empty list [] if no hosts added yet)

# 5. Frontend is being served by Nginx
curl -I http://127.0.0.1
# Expected: 200 OK with content-type: text/html

# 6. All services survive a reboot
sudo reboot
# After reboot, SSH back in and re-run checks 1–5
```

### Step 5.11 — Confirm CORS is set correctly

The FastAPI app must only allow requests from the production domain. Verify the CORS config in `api/main.py`:

```bash
grep -n "allow_origins" ~/network-health-manager/api/main.py
```

Expected:

```python
allow_origins=["https://nethealth.example.com"],
```

`localhost:5173` must not be present in the production deployment. It is only used during local development.

